# Interpretation block

- "Residual framing broadly helps": overall RMSE drops >10% on both models
- "Residual helps torque-controlled only": tStep/TMS improve >20% but PLC/PMS flat or worse. Consistent with "torEst ≈ torDes + small term on torque profiles makes the residual a clean learning target, while on velocity-controlled profiles torEst is structurally different and the residual is noise."
- "Residual helps velocity-controlled only": PLC/PMS improve >20% but tStep/TMS flat or worse. Surprising, would mean torEst carries useful state during ringing that the v1 model failed to exploit when asked to predict torAct absolute.
- "Residual helps everywhere except PLC": all profiles improve except PLC. Identifies PLC as uniquely broken and needing its own treatment.
- "Residual neutral": everything moves <5%. Means the v1 models were already implicitly learning the residual, and the explicit framing adds no signal.
- "Residual hurts": any degradation. Report which profile dominates the hurt.

Architecture-convergence check: if corr(pred_mlp, pred_gru) stays ≥ 0.995, the residual framing did not break the convergence (the two architectures still produce near-identical predictions and the bottleneck is upstream of the target choice). If corr drops below 0.99, the residual framing genuinely frees the architectures to diverge — interesting either way.

# Requirements

- Residual statistics must be logged before training so we know what the network was optimizing.
- Inference reconstruction must be sanity-checked with an assertion: reconstruction error on the TRAINING set should match the training loss (up to the scaler's normalization). If these disagree by >1%, there is a bug in the reconstruction.
- Do NOT overwrite v1 artefacts.
- Per-profile stratification uses the same filename-based logic as Prompt 11. If Prompt 11 has produced a reusable classifier function, import it rather than duplicating.

